-- Argos, Almacenes Exito, Petrobras, Wal-Mex: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Alexander Cuadros
-- 2010-07-20T03:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-20/argos-almacenes-exito-petrobras-wal-mex-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  rose for the first time in
four days, gaining 0.7 percent to 3,809.87. In Brazil, preferred
shares usually are the most-traded class of stock.  
 Brazil  
 Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BS): BlackRock Inc., the
world’s biggest asset manager, sold Petrobras shares last
quarter from its Latin America funds after Brazil’s state-
controlled oil company said it may sell $25 billion in stock.
Petrobras rose 0.4 percent to 26.95 reais.  
 Colombia  
 Almacenes Exito SA  (EXITO CB): Colombia’s retail sales rose
13.1 percent in May from a year earlier, the national statistics
agency said today. Economists had forecast an 8.2 percent
increase in sales, according to the median estimate of 7
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. Exito, Colombia’s biggest
publicly traded retailer, rose 0.9 percent to 18,700 pesos.  
 Cementos Argos SA  (CEMARGOS CB): Colombia’s industrial
production rose 7.5 percent in May from a year earlier, the
statistics agency said. Economists had forecast an 8.5 percent
increase in output, according to the median estimate of 8
analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. Argos, Colombia’s biggest cement
maker, fell 0.5 percent to 11,600 pesos.  
 Mexico  
 Wal-Mart de Mexico SAB  (WALMEXV MM): Mexico’s biggest
retailer reported second-quarter profit rose 24 percent after it
acquired the Central American unit of parent company Wal-Mart
Stores Inc this year. Net income was 4.65 billion pesos ($360
million) during the quarter, up from 3.75 billion pesos a year
ago. Shares rose 0.6 percent to 29.73 pesos.  
